## §31 — HOOKS PLACEMENT DOCTRINE
All React hooks (useState, useEffect, useQuery, useMutation) MUST be declared
BEFORE any conditional return statement in a component. No exceptions.

Placing hooks after early returns violates React Rules of Hooks and causes
silent crash (blank page, no error in console, no error boundary catch).

Root cause: React tracks hooks by call order. If an early return skips a hook
on one render but not another, the hook count changes → React internal state
corrupts → component unmounts silently.

Pattern: if you need a useEffect that depends on data from a query, use the
query's data directly in JSX or compute the value inline. Do NOT add useEffect
after the early return guard.

PROVEN: 2197 auto-expand crash. useEffect at L181 (before destructure) = temporal
dead zone. Moved to L412 (after destructure but after early return) = Rules of Hooks
violation. Both crashed the page. Reverted.

E3592DC3.


