## §35 — CHAINED REPLACE DOCTRINE
When a deploy script chains multiple string replacements on the same file,
later replacements may fail silently if earlier replacements already modified
the target region.

Example: FIX 1 changes "52+" to "105+" globally. FIX 3a targets a block
containing "52+" — but it's already "105+" from FIX 1. FIX 3a silently skips.

RULE: When chaining replaces that touch overlapping regions, always use the
POST-replacement text as the target for subsequent fixes, or restructure
the script so each fix operates on the already-modified content.

PROVEN: 2213 homepage deploy. FIX 3a skipped because FIX 1 already ran.
No harm in this case, but could cause missed fixes in others. E3592DC3.
